{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Failure boundary is model judgment quality: whether the reply actually grounds itself in thread-specific details versus generic text. A stubbed/mocked model would hide this because it can be forced to always return grounded output. Not Workflow because this behavior targets one model decision (reply generation), not multiple agentic decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Run the real LLM on representative real email threads and score each draft for explicit references to thread-specific facts (names, decisions, dates, asks). Fail if drafts are generic or miss key thread points across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior text anchors a module handoff failure: draft claims must be compared against KB entries and contradiction flags must propagate. This is best caught with multiple local modules wired together (draft parser/claim extractor, KB lookup, contradiction detector). Rejected Agentic because the behavior does not state that contradiction detection depends on real model judgment; no explicit LLM/ML dependence is given for this check.","test_description":"Wire the fact-check pipeline with an in-process KB fixture and a drafted email containing known contradictory claims; assert contradiction flags are emitted with correct claim references and severity.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the